<DOC><DOCNO> AP890302-0173 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2113EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-SovietEmigres     03-02 0185</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet Emigres,180</SECOND><HEAD>US Reviewing Refugee Policy Because of Numerous Soviet Applicants</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The State Department said Thursday it isreviewing its immigration policy in order to accommodate the largenumber of Jewish and other applicants from the Soviet Union.   Department spokesman Charles Redman said 13,000 Soviets arrivedin Vienna during the four-month period starting on Oct. 1 and thevast majority have requested resettlement in the United States.   Many of these individuals have already proceeded to Rome wherethey may make formal refugee applications, he said, adding that noone is being denied entry to the United States.   ``As of Jan. 31, some 3,400 individuals were awaiting theirrefugee interviews in Rome,'' he said. ``An additional 1,850 wereapproved and pending departure to the United States.''   He said the overall backlog at the end of January was less than7,000.   The administration is reviewing its refugee policy and examiningseveral options to address the increase in Soviet emigration as wellas other refugee issues, he said.   ``We will consult with the Congress when we have specific actionsto propose,'' he added.</TEXT></DOC>